The course examines both legal and political aspects of the United Nations. The introductory lectures are devoted to the idea and history behind the establishment of the organisation. Then, in the seminars, the issues like the nature, relevance and legal status of the charter, structure, membership, financing, conflict prevention and peace operations, peace-building and sanctions, development and self-determination, human rights and humanitarian assistance, immunity and responsibility as well as reform proposals are discussed.Objectives/eesmärkid:  To provide a comprehensive understanding of the history, purposes, structure, practice and challenges of the United Nations with an emphasis on legal aspectsLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has passed the course: -- Outlines the history of the United Nations and recognises the role of the organisation in world politics -- Explains the purposes and functioning principles of the organisation -- Describes the structure of the organisation and how the organisation and its specialised agencies are functioning -- Points out the fields where the organisation is active and judges what has been achieved and where the progress is lagging -- Identifies political and legal arguments used in discussions and comprehends the decision-making processes in the organisation
